snippet.textDisplay:
I have many, many differently rooted problems with this movie. The one that stood out to me first that I don't hear enough people talk about was how poorly edited this movie was.
I've seen and enjoyed fast paced movies with multiple action scenes happening parallel to each other, so I'm not universally against fast-cutting action, but the editing work in The Rise of Skywalker was honestly atrocious and jarring.
Everything felt rush, they jumped from scene to scene in the messiest way I've seen in a cinema movie in a Long time, and nothing was allowed to take time and sink in. You honestly got brain whiplash from watching this movie for the majority of its run-time. That has nothing to do with the writing, the acting, respecting the franchise's legacy or any of that bigger stuff that this movie doesn't do well. Simply as a stand-alone movie, the plain experience of watching it as a simple distraction happening on a big screen, wasn't enjoyable.
This movie really felt under-cocked and unfinished.

snippet.textDisplay: I dunno, I liked it. Maybe half of that is relief over the movies finally being over with. This was such a mess of a trilogy, even the prequels, as boring and dumb as they were felt like they tied into each other with some resemblance of cohesion. This felt like two directors fighting over who gets to play with Star Wars until they broke Disney's little toy into several pieces, and they refused to work well together to glue the whole thing back. You can still enjoy each section individually to some degree, but they barely provide backbone for one another. It's a mess, but I'm glad I was fortunate enough to enjoy it. Can't wait for the inevitably far more fun Lego games and spin-offs because that's really the Star Wars I grew up with. Here's hoping Lego SW3: Clone Wars wasn't the last good Lego Star Wars.

snippet.textDisplay: I just hope that Hollywood learns it's lesson with this disastrous trilogy. Yeah we like shiny things and explosions, but that's not the foundation of any film. Icing is great, but if the cake isn't any good it ruins the whole thing. Simply casting "diverse" actors isn't enough. You have to make the characters real. The fans didn't dislike the films because Rey isn't a dude and Finn is black. Those things aren't important honestly. Cast whatever race and/or gender you like, just pick the best people for the job, don't pick the race and gender first. One of the chief complained with the OT is that Leia seemed to be pretty much the only woman in the whole galaxy (although I count four, which still isn't very many). Alright then put more women in the films but don't make it so obvious that the actors practically turn to the audience and say "Look! There's nothing but women in this scene!" Same goes for race "Look! No white people!". With all that money I find it hard to believe Disney couldn't hire the best writers money can buy, so why the awful writing? Again, I hope Hollywood doesn't think "Ok, they don't like women and non-white people in Star Wars so we won't do that any more".
